I have another suggestion... we don't necessarily need to do this much.
There should be _two_ autopilot systems. One is capable of getting you from
any point in space to the atmosphere of a planet, moving at a safe re-entry
speed; the other can guide you from one point on a planet's surface to
another.

As an example: You're going from Titan City to New San Francisco. You
pick New SF on the system map and off you go... Autopilot 1 just takes
you straight to Earth, leaving you sitting somewhere on Earth 40,000
meters up. It hands off control to Autopilot 2, which flies you around
the planet on a Great Circle route to New San Francisco and lands you.

The beauty of this is you can also do long transcontinental or
oceanic flights while still being able to admire the view... if you
fly from New SF to New York, Autopilot 2 is handling you the whole time
and safely flies you there. You can fly at any time compression you
want, of course; no cheating is necessary.

The autopilots don't necessarily have to be _brilliant_ -- there needs
to occasionally be something for the human pilot to do. If, say, Jupiter
interposes itself between you and Earth, that's bad luck and you must
take manual control to get around it. Other than that, the autopilot is
extremely safe.

I like this idea. What do others think?

