I don't think too many people have commented on this, but it seems to
me that the reason the autopilot crashes so frequently when landing on planets
is this:

The autopilot plots it's course to your destination on a _straight line_
This means that if you are on the opposite side of a plantet from the port
you are landing on, the auto pilot is trying to get there by *going through
the planet*.  In order for this to be fixed, a whole system of navigation
while avoiding solid objects needs to be implemented.  As it stands, all there
seems to be is 'Go straight from point A to point B'

Now that still doesn't address the fact that the autopilot almost always does
not slow down in time to avoid crashing in to objects, even vwhen it is pro-
perly aligned with them.  This is probably csaused by figuring all movment
based on the power of the main thrusters. (Which are more powerful than
the retros) To fix this, the autopilot shluld either flip the ship, so tha6t
it actually does use the main thrusters to slow the ship, ur or adjust the
calculations using the trhust of the drive it is actually going to use.

(Of course it a is also possible that it is caused by the relative - to
- wrong- body bug)

Quentin Mohos  mohos@eden.rutgers.edu

