I'm surprised nobody noticed this yet.  Everybody seems to think that the 
multi-galaxy thing is some kinda of bug.  I think it's actually the 
scheme they used to compress the galaxy.  I'm sure everybody has heard 
of fractal compression at one time or another but has never really seen 
it, well I havn't seen a better example yet.  The multi-galaxy thing tips 
it off, what really gives it away is something I tried once.  I stuck a 
nickel in the zoom out key on the galaxy map, left for awhile, came back, 
took the nickel out, and guess what I saw.

I saw one big dotty milky way made out of many many small milky ways.  
Now it could be jumping the gun, but I think that leads to the 
conclussion that Frontier uses fractal compress to store the galaxy, and 
why you see other galaxys when you zoom out, those galaxies form one big 
galaxy, and a bunch of those big galaxys from a really big galaxy and so 
on..

(I did this on a PC, but I'm sure it's the same for Amiga)
 

-- 
