> Your mileage may vary.
> In Germany, court decisions said that you buying the program makes
> everything, including the code, your property. The 'Licenses' are
> therefore not necessarily valid in Germany (read the "c't" for this).
> 
> Otoh, decompiling the program might be still illegal due to Copyright
> violations...

Copyright laws are there to prevent people from copying and *spreading* the
material, it doesn't apply to reverse engineering. What's more, I find it
*immoral* for a software company to tell me what I can or can't do with the
piece of code I just purchased. Imagine I would be send to jail for writing
comments in the margin of a book! That's why hacking out copy protection
will be valid to a judge, regardless of what the license agreement says.
Semi-proof: would ftp.wustl.edu take the chance of police shutting the
computer down because they distribute patches to remove protection from
lots of PC-wares? Still, they do spread them, since (a) there's (legally
and morally) nothing wrong with getting rid of your own copy's protection,
and (b) the patches are all *new* products, for which the author of the
patch holds the copyright, not the author of the program that will be
patched.

But if you would decompile Frontier to use Braben's vectorgraphics
routines, than copyright laws will apply (and you're in trouble...). Even
if you decompile for learning purposes only, and not intend to copy the
code into your own programs, you're in fact stealing Braben's knowledge,
since he didn't make his programming techniques public (i.e. he should have
written a book on it, or make the source available).
