In case you (or someone else) has not figured this out yet....

FRONTIER'S GALAXY IS NOT OUR GALAXY

Not even close. The closest stars to Sol are pretty much correct,
but after 20 ly or so, everything is made up. Planets etc
are naturally made up. (With pretty good planet formation
routines I suppose) 

Galaxy is much much thicker than under 20ly and it's thickness
varies very much. Frontier's Galaxy map is only pseudo-3d. In reality
you really don't need the 3rd dimension, as the galaxy is paper-thin.

Braben has added few notable stars (Beta Lyrae for example) but
there's less than 100 stars that have their real counterparts.
99.9999% of the galaxy is made up with some clever fractal-style
routine.

IMHO this sucks bigtime. I must admit a realistic starmap
would be...
1. bit too much for joe gamesplayer as it would be REALLY 3D. there
would be stars in every direction from sol for at least 100-200 ly.
(I'm no astronomer, I just pulled this number off the hat. Correct
if you have better info)

2. bit too much for frontier game disk. I belive few hundred
thousand stars have been mapped and named (numeric names for most
of them but anyway) (I'm no astronomer, correct me if I'm wrong)
and adding a 1:1 starmap with 'randomly' added stars as
the distance from sol grows (you don't have to go far before
you can only see the brightest ones from sol) would
take tons of disk space.

3. bit too much for ANY gamesplayer. 99% of the gamers wouldn't
visit a fraction of those systems anyway.

